                <h3><a name="usecase">What can you blogwith for?</a></h3>

                <p>Blogwith is created for the ease of managing your Wordpress site straight from Evernote editor. You can write up a note in Evernote and have it published straight to Wordpress in seconds.</p>

                <p>However, the one thing that it does best is <strong>Live Blogging</strong>. The changes in the connected note content takes place immediately in your Wordpress post. Imagine you are at a live event and you are taking notes of the live presentation, you can have these notes be published to your Wordpress site in real time.</p>

                <h3><a name="howitworks">How it works?</a></h3>

                <p>Blogwith works with Evernote tags. </p>

                <p>When you connect your account with Blogwith, a <strong><em>&#8220;BlogwithPublish&#8221;<strong>* notebook will appear in your Evernote account. This </strong></em>&#8220;BlogwithPublish&#8221;</strong>* notebook is the key to using Blogwith.</p>

                <p>Any note within <strong><em>&#8220;BlogwithPublish&#8221;<strong>* notebook with a tag of </strong></em>&#8220;bw_published&#8221;</strong>* will be published to the connected Wordpress site.</p>

                <p>Any note within <strong><em>&#8220;BlogwithPublish&#8221;<strong>* notebook with a tag of </strong></em>&#8220;bw_markdown&#8221;</strong>* will be published as markdown to the connected Wordpress site.</p>

                <h3><a name="writingmarkdown">How to write markdown in Evernote?</a></h3>

                <p>Any note within <strong><em>&#8220;BlogwithPublish&#8221;<strong>* notebook with a tag of </strong></em>&#8220;bw_markdown&#8221;</strong>* will be published as markdown to the connected Wordpress site. </p>

                <p>So to publish a markdown post, you will need to have two tags in the Evernote note. <strong><em>&#8220;bw_markdown&#8221;<strong>* &amp; </strong></em>&#8220;bw_published&#8221;</strong>*</p>

                <blockquote>
                <p>Markdown was initially created by John Gruber (of Daring Fireball) as a simple way for non-programming types to write in an easy-to-read format that could be converted directly into HTML. via <a href="http://lifehacker.com/5943320/what-is-markdown-and-why-is-it-better-for-my-to-do-lists-and-notes">Link</a></p>
                </blockquote>

                <p>You can learn more about Markdown syntax <a href="http://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/syntax">here</a></p>

                <p>Blogwith will process the Evernote content into Markdown. However you would also need to setup your Wordpress to receive Markdown. This can be done in the following manner:</p>

                <ul>
                <li>Go to your Wordpress admin page</li>
                <li>Go to Settings</li>
                <li>Go to Writing</li>
                </ul>

                <p>You should see this:
                <img src="http://note.io/1ABMBx5" alt="Writing settings" /></p>

                <ul>
                <li>You should check the box, save changes and you are done.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>You can try out this post, remember to tag it with <strong>bw_markdown</strong> and <strong>bw_published</strong></p>

                <h3><a name="tags">What are the Tags we can use now?</a></h3>

                <p>Here is a list of Tags that Blogwith processes now. It will get biweekly updates</p>

                <ul>
                <li>bw_published: This is to published the post</li>
                <li>bw_markdown: This is to tell blogwith to have the note processed into markdown.</li>
                </ul>

                <h3><a name="export">Exporting data?</a></h3>

                <p>Blogwith is not a blogging service. The source is <a href="https://evernote.com/contact/support/kb/#!/article/28607737">Evernote</a> and the destination is <a href="https://en.support.wordpress.com/export/">Wordpress</a>. Both of these services allow you to export data out easily. I have added the links to exporting out from both of these services.</p>

